e around the bend.<br>
 I must assume they've lost some faith in our species' responsibility and ability to use things for good instead of bad. I haven't (though I'm not an optimistic young squirt either).<br>
<br>
 Questions about their views on Orion, if they're both staunchly against it:<br>
 Are we talking about the old fission-bomb ground-launch monster? Are they unable to separate the fallout danger of this from a space-only use?<br>
Is there any optimism about something like the 10 meter, 500 ton upper stage ship, or would safety require it to be completely space-only, above the Van Allen belts?<br>
I fail to see <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>any</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> risk from this, unless you've completely lost faith in our ability to secure the chain of bomb production from diversion by terrorists (Given the fact that we've forbidden airline pilots from carrying nail clippers, this must be the case, so maybe I am hopelessly optimistic).<br>
<br>
(Edited to expand on some thoughts)<br>
 If the danger of Pu proliferation also includes governments secretly diverting Pu to make new weapons, then this also should be workable. If, as has been <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm9.showMessage?topicID=8.topic">suggested</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, we use dismantled warheads, then a multinational system of accounting is already implied, so it's not much of a stretch to imagine an NPR ship -especially since it would necessarily mean permanent disposal of the Pu.<br>
