</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=moybin>moybin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/8/02 4:23:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=69.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Nuclear Propulsion</span><hr size=1> For the same reasons that a pusher plate CAN survive close nuclear explosions, a surface nuclear explosion/launch is better conducted from a hard rock site than an ocean site.  <br>
<br>
Yes, the fireball sucks up surface debris (dust) and activates it.  But there is only so much rock dust at the launch site.  A sea-based launch sucks up TONS of seawater which contains a LOT of metal ions which become activated.  An underwater or ocean surface detonation is the absolute dirtiest route to go.  Rather launch from someplace with very hard, heat resistant surface, like Sierra Nevada granite or possibly old lava beds.  Basalt is compressed lava, probably the very best launch surface we could find.<br>
<br>
The pusher plate thing: you make it out of Aluminum, not steel.  Aluminum has only one radioactive isotope, and that has a 5 minute half-life.  10 half-lives or 50 minutes later and it is effectively non-radioactive.  It is very conductive thermally, so cools rapidly.  Yes, it has a lower melting point, but that can be engineered around.<br>
<br>
Larry Niven in FOOTFALL resurrected the Orion.  He envisioned a ship large enough to have 4 space shuttles strapped to the outside of the command module.  Entirely feasable.<br>
<br>
Also, collectively the nations of the Earth have detonated hundreds of various sized weapons in the atmosphere.  To detonate another dozen or so, and really clean ones at that, is entirely within what the environment could handle.  Sierra Clubbers would picket right up to the moment of launch, but I would bet they were back 20 miles or more.  No sense getting killed over your own hairbrained ideas.<br>
<br>
I, too, included the Orion drive, in my first published book.  Check out my post elsewhere on this forum under:<br>
